{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PszmVkcgJzLViQpJfXQbaG","type":"tool_result","content":"The file /root/clawd/epiphany-learn/content/module-5/lesson-3-questions-before-buying.mdx has been updated successfully."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f35b7b4d-e00d-4a46-b7f3-fc8a38b8e426","uuid":"c5e5ca28-6ba1-47aa-8086-4dac3f7e5bec","timestamp":"2026-03-28T00:03:41.103Z","tool_use_result":{"filePath":"/root/clawd/epiphany-learn/content/module-5/lesson-3-questions-before-buying.mdx","oldString":"  reveal=\"Don't ask 'do you integrate with [Tool X]?' — ask to see the integration work in a live demo with real data. Ask: is it bidirectional? Does it handle errors and retries? Is it maintained by the vendor or by a third-party connector service? An integration that breaks silently can corrupt your data without you knowing.\"","newString":"  reveal={\"Don't ask 'do you integrate with [Tool X]?' — ask to see the integration work in a live demo with real data. Ask: is it bidirectional? Does it handle errors and retries? Is it maintained by the vendor or by a third-party connector service? An integration that breaks silently can corrupt your data without you knowing.\"}","originalFile":"---\nid: lesson-3\nmoduleId: module-5\nslug: questions-before-buying\ntitle: \"12 Questions to Ask Before You Buy\"\nsubtitle: \"The buyer's checklist that cuts through the demo magic\"\nestimatedMinutes: 8\nxpReward: 50\n---\n\n# 12 Questions to Ask Before You Buy\n\nThe best time to ask hard questions about an AI tool is before you've signed up, integrated your data, and built workflows around it. After that, switching costs make you a captive customer.\n\nHere's a checklist of 12 questions that actually matter. Run every serious purchase through it.\n\n---\n\n## Why Most Evaluations Fail\n\nMost people evaluate AI tools on one dimension: **can it do the thing in the demo?**\n\nThat's necessary but not sufficient. You also need to know:\n- What happens when it fails?\n- What does it cost at scale?\n- How hard is it to leave?\n- Who owns the outputs it generates?\n\nThese questions don't get asked because the vendor doesn't volunteer them — and buyers are caught up in the excitement of what the tool *can* do.\n\n---\n\n## The 12 Questions\n\n<RevealCard\n  id=\"q-1\"\n  label=\"1. What specific problem does this solve — and what's my baseline without it?\"\n  reveal=\"Write down, in one sentence, what this tool does for you. Then calculate your current cost or effort for that same task without the tool. If you can't articulate the before/after clearly, you're not ready to buy. This isn't a vendor question — it's a homework question. Do it before the first demo.\"\n/>\n\n<RevealCard\n  id=\"q-2\"\n  label=\"2. What does the actual onboarding process look like, step by step?\"\n  reveal=\"Ask for the full onboarding timeline: kickoff call, data connection, configuration, testing, go-live. Who does the work — you, their team, or a partner? How long does it realistically take to get value? 'Up in 5 minutes' is usually accurate for the login screen. Getting it to work well takes longer.\"\n/>\n\n<RevealCard\n  id=\"q-3\"\n  label=\"3. What does it cost at 3x and 10x my current usage?\"\n  reveal=\"AI pricing often scales aggressively. A tool that costs $99/month at your current usage can balloon to $800/month if you actually rely on it. Ask for the pricing table at 3x and 10x your projected volume. Ask what triggers a tier upgrade and whether there are usage caps or throttling below the limit.\"\n/>\n\n<RevealCard\n  id=\"q-4\"\n  label=\"4. What happens when the AI gets it wrong?\"\n  reveal=\"Every AI tool makes mistakes. Ask: how do errors surface (do you see them, or do they silently fail)? What's the process to report and fix errors? Is there a human review option? Does the tool include confidence scores so you know when to verify outputs? The vendor's answer here tells you a lot about how honest they are about their own product.\"\n/>\n\n<RevealCard\n  id=\"q-5\"\n  label=\"5. Who owns the outputs this tool generates?\"\n  reveal=\"If the tool writes copy, creates designs, generates code, or produces content — who owns that output? Most standard ToS give you ownership of outputs, but some terms are murkier. Check especially if you're in a regulated industry or if intellectual property rights matter for your use case. This is a ToS review question, not a sales question.\"\n/>\n\n<RevealCard\n  id=\"q-6\"\n  label=\"6. Is my data used to train the model?\"\n  reveal=\"The honest answer from most enterprise AI vendors is 'no, with a signed DPA.' The honest answer from most consumer or prosumer AI tools is 'yes, by default unless you opt out' — and the opt-out may not be retroactive. Check the privacy policy and the Data Processing Agreement. If neither document exists or isn't accessible, assume your data trains the model.\"\n/>\n\n<RevealCard\n  id=\"q-7\"\n  label=\"7. What does the cancellation process look like?\"\n  reveal=\"Ask before you start: how do I cancel? How much notice is required? What happens to my data after I cancel? How long is it retained? Can I export everything? If the cancellation path is unclear or convoluted, assume it's designed to be. The best vendors make cancellation as easy as signup — because they're confident you'll stay.\"\n/>\n\n<RevealCard\n  id=\"q-8\"\n  label=\"8. What's the service's uptime track record and SLA?\"\n  reveal=\"If this tool becomes part of your workflow, its downtime is your downtime. Ask for their status page URL and look at the last 90 days of uptime data. Ask what the SLA is on their paid plan and what compensation you get for missed SLAs. No published uptime history = they're not confident in their reliability.\"\n/>\n\n<RevealCard\n  id=\"q-9\"\n  label=\"9. Can I talk to 2-3 customers in my situation before committing?\"\n  reveal=\"Not the polished case studies on their website — actual customers who use the tool for something close to your use case. Ask them: what doesn't work well? What took longer than expected? Would you buy it again? Vendors who won't connect you with references are hiding something. Vendors who can't find references for your use case may not have solved your problem yet.\"\n/>\n\n<RevealCard\n  id=\"q-10\"\n  label=\"10. What integrations do I actually need — and how deep are they?\"\n  reveal=\"Don't ask 'do you integrate with [Tool X]?' — ask to see the integration work in a live demo with real data. Ask: is it bidirectional? Does it handle errors and retries? Is it maintained by the vendor or by a third-party connector service? An integration that breaks silently can corrupt your data without you knowing.\"\n/>\n\n<RevealCard\n  id=\"q-11\"\n  label=\"11. What's your roadmap for the next 6-12 months — and what's guaranteed vs. aspirational?\"\n  reveal=\"If you're buying partly based on upcoming features, separate the roadmap into two buckets: committed (contractually guaranteed by a specific date) and aspirational (planned but subject to change). Don't pay today for aspirational features. If a feature is truly critical to your use case, get a contractual commitment or wait until it ships.\"\n/>\n\n<RevealCard\n  id=\"q-12\"\n  label=\"12. What does a failed implementation look like — and how common is it?\"\n  reveal=\"This question makes bad vendors uncomfortable and good vendors appreciative. Ask: what are the most common reasons implementations fail with customers like me? What would you do differently with a customer in my situation? What percentage of customers who sign up don't achieve the outcomes they expected? Vendors who can answer this honestly have learned from failures — that's a green flag.\"\n/>\n\n---\n\n## The Pre-Buy Checklist (Print This)\n\nBefore signing any AI tool contract, confirm you've answered:\n\n- [ ] I can state the specific problem this solves in one sentence\n- [ ] I know the full cost at 3x my current usage\n- [ ] I've seen it run on my actual messy data, not just demo data\n- [ ] I know exactly how to cancel and export my data\n- [ ] I've checked: is my data used for model training?\n- [ ] I've spoken with at least one reference customer in a similar situation\n- [ ] I know what \"wrong\" looks like and how errors surface\n- [ ] I've reviewed the ToS for output ownership\n- [ ] I know the onboarding timeline and who does the work\n- [ ] Any roadmap features I'm depending on are contractually committed\n\nIf you can't check all 10 boxes, you're not done evaluating yet.\n\n---\n\n## Quick Check\n\n<Quiz\n  id=\"lesson-3-quiz\"\n  questions={[\n    {\n      id: \"q1\",\n      text: \"A vendor's roadmap shows a key feature you need is 'coming in Q3.' What's the right approach?\",\n      options: [\n        { id: \"a\", text: \"Buy now to lock in current pricing and get the feature when it ships\" },\n        { id: \"b\", text: \"Get a contractual commitment with a refund clause if Q3 slips, or wait until it ships\" },\n        { id: \"c\", text: \"Ask the vendor to prioritize the feature for you since you're a paying customer\" },\n        { id: \"d\", text: \"Accept the roadmap as a reliable commitment — vendors always deliver on schedule\" }\n      ],\n      correctId: \"b\",\n      explanation: \"Roadmap promises are aspirational by default. If a feature is critical to your use case, either get it in writing with a specific delivery date and refund clause, or wait until it ships. Buying based on uncontracted promises is how businesses end up paying for products that don't yet do what they need.\"\n    },\n    {\n      id: \"q2\",\n      text: \"You ask a vendor for 2-3 customer references in a similar situation to yours. They say they can't share customer contact info due to privacy. What should you conclude?\",\n      options: [\n        { id: \"a\", text: \"This is a reasonable privacy policy and not a concern\" },\n        { id: \"b\", text: \"This is suspicious — reputable vendors can provide opt-in references from willing customers\" },\n        { id: \"c\", text: \"They likely don't have any customers yet\" },\n        { id: \"d\", text: \"Ask for written testimonials instead — those are equivalent\" }\n      ],\n      correctId: \"b\",\n      explanation: \"Reputable vendors maintain a pool of willing reference customers who have opted in to speak with prospects. A blanket 'privacy' refusal usually means they don't have satisfied customers in your use case, or they have concerns about what references would say. Written testimonials are carefully curated — they're not a substitute for an unscripted conversation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      id: \"q3\",\n      text: \"Which of these is the most important question to ask before signing an AI tool contract?\",\n      options: [\n        { id: \"a\", text: \"What's the current number of active users on the platform?\" },\n        { id: \"b\", text: \"What does it cost at 10x my current usage volume?\" },\n        { id: \"c\", text: \"Which VC firm funded the company?\" },\n        { id: \"d\", text: \"How many features does the tool have vs. competitors?\" }\n      ],\n      correctId: \"b\",\n      explanation: \"AI pricing scales in ways that aren't obvious from the starter plan. Understanding the cost at 10x usage tells you whether this tool is viable long-term or whether it becomes unaffordable if you actually adopt it widely. Feature count and VC backing are vanity metrics that don't predict whether the tool will work for you.\"\n    }\n  ]}\n/>\n\n---\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\n> **The point of these questions isn't to find a reason to say no. It's to make sure that when you say yes, you've said yes to the tool you'll actually be using — not the one that looked good in the demo.**\n\n---\n\n<LessonComplete lessonId=\"lesson-3\" nextLessonSlug=\"pricing-and-build-vs-buy\" xpReward={50} />\n","structuredPatch":[{"oldStart":89,"oldLines":7,"newStart":89,"newLines":7,"lines":[" <RevealCard","   id=\"q-10\"","   label=\"10. What integrations do I actually need — and how deep are they?\"","-  reveal=\"Don't ask 'do you integrate with [Tool X]?' — ask to see the integration work in a live demo with real data. Ask: is it bidirectional? Does it handle errors and retries? Is it maintained by the vendor or by a third-party connector service? An integration that breaks silently can corrupt your data without you knowing.\"","+  reveal={\"Don't ask 'do you integrate with [Tool X]?' — ask to see the integration work in a live demo with real data. Ask: is it bidirectional? Does it handle errors and retries? Is it maintained by the vendor or by a third-party connector service? An integration that breaks silently can corrupt your data without you knowing.\"}"," />"," "," <RevealCard"]}],"userModified":false,"replaceAll":false}}
